originalText.text: During automated check-in, I stated that my sister had no insurance, as she is a Medicare recipient from another state.  Staff could have accepted that answer, but they did some research and found that her out-of-state policy covered urgent care in New York.  From the front desk to the nurses and doctor, all staff were super helpful.  They tested both of us for a full range of respiratory illnesses, and gave great advice about how we could relieve our symptoms.  We give them an A+ for their caring, understanding, efficiency, and for saving us a lot of out-of-pocket money.  (As a side note, a man in the lobby wanted ER psychiatry services on-site, and he became caustic when they referred him to a hospital ER.  Impressive how professionally and effectively they handled him.)

originalText.text:
DO NOT GO TO CITYMD FOR A COVID TEST. I recently went to CityMD for a COVID test, and my experience has left me extremely frustrated and disappointed. Receiving an unexpected bill for over $400 is unacceptable, especially considering the availability of rapid tests for a minimal fee or even for free elsewhere.

Navigating through the ongoing public health challenge of COVID should not translate into facing such exorbitant expenses. It is essential for CityMD to be transparent about potential costs upfront, ensuring patients are well-informed before making decisions about their healthcare. It's disheartening to see a healthcare provider contribute to the challenges individuals face in these unprecedented times.

I hope my review serves as a cautionary note for others, prompting CityMD to reconsider their pricing practices and prioritize the well-being of their patients.

Will not be going back.
The front desk was SUPER NICE. Also the doctor assistant was nice to me as well.
My issue is with the DOCTOR. As a black woman myself, i expect other older black women to be kind to me. She was dry, sarcastic, wondering why i didnt like to take medication. She made me feel worse than i already felt. She was rude, and didnt help me at all. So I will be going downtown to a "nicer" part of town next time.

originalText.text: The doctor scoffed that I had kept my daughter home from school for 4 days. She told me that since her temperature was not very high, I should send her to school. So, I did, even thought her throat hurt and she felt bad. Then, 2.5 days after the exam, they finally call to tell us her strep test was positive! I sent my daughter to school with strep. And now her little brother has strep too.
